# Assumptions and Limitations

## Purpose

This document describes the assumptions and limitations of this exploratory quantum-inspired omics benchmarking repository.

## Assumptions

- The example dataset is simulated and used only for workflow demonstration.
- The simulated data represent a high-dimensional omics-style structure, with more features than biological groups.
- A small group-associated signal is added to selected features to support method benchmarking.
- Classical PCA and kernel-based modelling are used as baseline approaches.
- The workflow is designed to demonstrate reproducible structure, not final biological interpretation.

## Limitations

- The repository does not yet implement a true quantum computing model.
- The current scripts use classical machine-learning and statistical approaches.
- The simulated dataset is simplified and does not capture all properties of real omics data.
- Real omics datasets may include batch effects, missing values, compositional constraints, technical noise and complex biological confounders.
- The current benchmarking does not yet include quantum simulators, quantum kernels or quantum machine-learning libraries.

## Future extensions

Future versions of this repository may include:

- quantum-inspired feature mapping
- kernel comparison across linear, polynomial and radial basis function methods
- comparison with classical dimensionality reduction methods
- integration with Qiskit or PennyLane
- quantum kernel simulations
- benchmarking on public omics datasets
- reporting of computational cost, interpretability and model limitations

## Relevance to quantum omics

This repository documents an active transition from classical statistical omics workflows toward quantum-inspired approaches for high-dimensional biological data.

It is intended to support transparent, reproducible and critically evaluated method development at the interface of omics, statistics and quantum-enabled data analysis.
